<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-487-035  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 487 035.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 24 1990 v12 n39 p47(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Applications now offer features in System 7.0; separate programssave RAM and money. (Apple Macintosh System 7.0 operating system)(Macintosh News - Technology Update)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lach, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Third-party vendors offer applications packages and utilityprograms that provide many of the features the overdue AppleMacintosh System 7.0 operating system is supposed to have.andO;Industry analysts are skeptical that Apple Computer Inc willreally deliver the new System 7.0 by the end of 1990.andP;  Thus, oneadvantage to the third-party software is their currentavailability.andP;  Connectix Corp already has its Virtual program thatlets a Macintosh operate as if it has more RAM than it reallydoes.andP;  Type Manager from Adobe Systems Inc provides the fontoutlining capabilities that are expected with Apple's TrueTypemodule.andP;  In addition to availability, if only one feature isneeded it may be less expensive to buy one application thanupgrade to System 7.0.andP;  These and other software publishersconsider their programs to be more robust than System 7.0 althoughApple argues that problems of compatibility may arise.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   System 7.0 (Operating system) (product development)Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (computer programs).andO;Topic:     Operating SystemsIndustry AnalysisUtility ProgramsProduct Delay.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Subbing for System 7...and what you could use in the meantime.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>